-- 
Philippine Stocks: Lopez, Philex, San Miguel, Universal Robina

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-05-12T04:49:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/philippine-equity-movers-san-miguel-universal-robina.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 0.5 percent to
4,312.01, its first loss in four days.  Lopez Holdings Corp. (LPZ)  , which has investments in
media and energy, climbed 3.1 percent to 6.70 pesos, the highest
level since April 2000. The company and its unit  ABS-CBN Corp. (ABS) 
 completed the sale of depositary receipts backed by
common shares in Sky Cable Corp., a stock exchange filing
showed. ABS-CBN gained 1.5 percent to 42 pesos.  Philex Mining Corp. (PX)  , the nation’s biggest producer
of metals, advanced 6.5 percent to 19.72 pesos, the highest
close based on prices going back to January 1990. The company
said it reached a final agreement with  Manila Mining Corp. (MAB)  to
explore and jointly develop the Kalayaan copper-gold project.  Manila Mining Class A shares (MA PM), which are reserved
for Filipinos, jumped 6.4 percent to 5 centavos, the highest
level since August 1995. Its Class B shares (MAB PM), which have
no ownership restrictions, climbed 6.4 percent to 5 centavos.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  , the nation’s biggest food and
drinks company, fell 3.1 percent to 110.90 pesos, the sharpest
loss since May 5.  San Miguel ’s debt rating outlook was cut to
“negative” from “stable” by Standard & Poor’s Financial
Services LLC, which said the company’s cash reserves may be
depleted by its expansion plans.  Universal Robina Corp. (URC)  , the nation’s second-
largest food and drinks company, increased 2.6 percent to 39.10
pesos, the highest close since Dec. 3. The company said
yesterday that it will pay 1.90 pesos a share in regular and
special dividends, the highest payout based on records going
back to 1995.  To contact the reporter on this story:
